RMarkdown Interactive Webpage Example


This page demonstates some nice functionality built both within and outside of R to generate multi-faceted, rich reports. The following is a synthetic report about Firefox add-ons, which is my focus as a member of Mozillas product data science team.

Tables

Do you even need a plot? Sometimes the answer is no, and if you can load a csv or the like into R you can render a nice html table using the kableExtra + knitr packages.

# make some fake data
fakeAggregates <- data.frame(
  addons=c(24.5, 3.4),
  no.addons=c(20.1, 2.3)
)
colnames(fakeAggregates) <- c("Addons", "No Addons")
rownames(fakeAggregates) <- c("Mean Session Length", "Mean Number of Sessions")

# render html table
fakeAggregates %>%
kable("html", escape=F) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"), full_width=F, font_size=25)
Addons No Addons
Mean Session Length 24.5 20.1
Mean Number of Sessions 3.4 2.3

Static Plots

Before getting all fancy, I evaluate the ggplot2 package to see if a simple, static plot will convey the information I want (usually it can!). This package has tons of customization options should you spend the time to read its docs :). Below is some more fake data from a hypothetical experiment.

generateFakeDataHist <- function(n) {
  histData <- data.frame(
    bucket=rep(1:n, 2),
    freq=100/(exp(rep(1:n, 2))+ (runif(1:(n*2)))),
    group=c(rep('Treatment', n), rep('Control', n))
  )
  histData
}

# how many buckets for the histogram?
N <- 5

# get some fake data
histData <- generateFakeDataHist(N)

# build the plot
p <- ggplot(histData) +
  geom_col(aes(x=bucket, y=freq, fill=group), alpha=.6, position="dodge") +
  theme(axis.line = element_line(colour = "#B3B2B2"),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "top",
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        text = element_text(family='sans')) + 
  labs(x="X", y="Percentage of Users (%)", title="Percentage of Users with X Add-ons for Treatment/Control") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:N) +
  scale_fill_manual("legend", values = c("Treatment" = "#05b378", "Control" = "#acabab"))

# add some text annotations
p + geom_text(data=histData, aes(x=bucket, y=freq, group=group,
                label=paste(round(freq, 2), "%", sep='')), 
            position=position_dodge(.9), vjust=-.25, size=2.5,)

Embedded HTML

Okay, so a table and a static plot arent doing the trick? We can develop plots using, say, D3.js outside of rmarkdown, and then link them into the resulting webpage. The following examples are generated with the metricsgraphics.js package, which is a wrapper for D3 that focuses on time series visualization.

The plots below show fake data for 3 of Firefoxs channels. The plots are linked, so when a user hovers over the plot area, the legend on each plot displays the numbers used to calculate the percentages shown: \[ \frac{Users\ with\ Addons}{Total\ Users} \]

This is useful for reporting metrics over time, without crowding the plot with a bunch of text annotations.



htmltools::includeHTML('./html/mg-charts.html')
